In Kubernetes, a taint on a node repels pods unless the pod has a matching toleration. The effect controls how strongly the scheduler/runtime enforces that repulsion.
1) NoSchedule

Meaning: Hard block for new pods.
Behavior: The scheduler will not place a pod on the node unless the pod tolerates the taint.
What it does not do: It doesn’t evict pods that are already running on that node.
When to use: Reserve nodes for specific workloads (e.g., GPU nodes, dedicated team nodes).

2) PreferNoSchedule

Meaning: Soft block (best-effort).
Behavior: The scheduler will try to avoid placing pods there, but may still schedule pods onto the node if it can’t find a better option (resource pressure, constraints, etc.).
What it does not do: It doesn’t evict existing pods.
When to use: “Keep off this node if possible” (e.g., nodes under maintenance observation, less-preferred capacity).

3) NoExecute

Meaning: Hard block + eviction.
Behavior:

New pods: won’t be scheduled unless they tolerate the taint.
Existing pods: get evicted if they don’t tolerate it.


Extra nuance: A pod toleration can include tolerationSeconds to stay temporarily before eviction (useful for brief node issues).
When to use: Enforce rapid removal from nodes (e.g., node not-ready scenarios, dedicated nodes where non-tolerating pods must be cleared).

Rule of thumb:

Need strict placement control → NoSchedule
Prefer avoidance but allow exceptions → PreferNoSchedule
Need to kick pods off nodes too → NoExecute

These phrases come from Kubernetes affinity/anti-affinity docs (nodeAffinity and podAffinity/podAntiAffinity). They describe two dimensions:

Hard vs soft rule


required... = hard requirement (must be met)
preferred... = soft preference (try best, but can violate)


When it is enforced


DuringScheduling... = enforced when the pod is being scheduled
...DuringExecution vs ...RequiredDuringExecution = what happens later if the world changes (labels change, node labels change, etc.)

Available (implemented today)
requiredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution

Hard at scheduling time: pod will schedule only onto nodes/pods that match.
Ignored during execution: if labels change after it’s running, Kubernetes does not evict the pod.

Example meaning: “Place this pod only on nodes with disktype=ssd; if the node label changes later, don’t move it.”
preferredDuringSchedulingIgnoredDuringExecution

Soft at scheduling time: scheduler will try to match (using weights), but can place it elsewhere.
Ignored during execution: no eviction later if things change.

Example meaning: “Prefer nodes in zone=us-east-1a, but run anywhere if needed.”
Planned (not generally available as a built-in enforcement)
These appear in older design discussions/docs as “Planned”:
requiredDuringSchedulingRequiredDuringExecution (planned)

Hard at scheduling time and would remain hard during runtime:
If the rule becomes false later, the pod would be evicted/relocated to re-satisfy the rule.

preferredDuringSchedulingRequiredDuringExecution (planned)

Soft preference at scheduling time, but would be enforced during runtime in some way (e.g., try to move pods to satisfy preference as conditions change).

Practical “so what” (how people handle runtime enforcement today)
Kubernetes generally doesn’t evict pods just because affinity stops matching (that’s the “IgnoredDuringExecution” part). If you need runtime enforcement, common patterns are:

Taints + NoExecute (to evict non-tolerating pods)
Descheduler (an add-on that can evict pods to rebalance/re-satisfy policies)
Policy + automation (controllers/operators) depending on platform
